To use TACT you must either select a set of words from the List
of words, or give TACT a search strategy whereby it can select a
list of words, or positions in the text that meet its
requirements.

   1.  If you have indicated that the base list is the list of
       words found in your text, then TACT's selection window
       (presented to you when you push F3) will show you a list
       of all the words in the text.  You can select words that
       interest you, to create the {B}Selected List{N}.

   2.  Instead of selecting from the list of words, you can ask
       TACT to preselect words or text positions for you.  You do
       this by either selecting {B}Rule{N} from the {B}Action Bar's Select{N}
       menu, or by pushing {B}F2{N} -- the short cut.

       If you have provided TACT with a Search Strategy (via F2)
       then the Selection Window (Short Cut: F3) will show all
       the words or positions that TACT selected.  You can then
       only select a subset of this list to create the {B}Selected{N}
       {B}List{N}.

   3.  When you are finished using a list created by a search
       strategy, and again wish to select words based on the
       entire vocabulary, you can indicate this by either
       selecting {B}WordList{N} from the {B}Action Bar Select{N} menu, or by
       pushing {B}Ctrl-F3{N} (which is TACT's shortcut).  In response,
       TACT will first throw away both the Search Result list it
       created, and the selected list.  However, you can then use
       the Selection Window ({B}F3{N}) to select from the list of
       words.

TACT uses the selected list to create displays: KWIC displays, a
text window with selected spots in the text highlighted, an
index, or a distribution list.  For more information on these,
type "{B}D{N}" now.


