Welcome to MAKBAS for TACT system 1.2.

The rest of this introduction message is a some information that
will help to get you started using MAKBAS.  To read more than
what shows on the screen, push the {B}PageDown{N} key.  To move "up" in
this text, push the {B}PageUp{N} key.


                       {B}What can I do now?{N}

Before you can make MAKBAS do anything else, you must finish
looking at Help.  Do this by pushing either the "Enter" or "ESC"
key.

MAKBAS is used to produce a textual database for TACT from an
input source text.  At this point you can do three things:

   1.  You can stop MAKBAS immediately by pushing the F10 key.

   2.  You can check over and alter if necessary the assumptions
       MAKBAS will make about the text file it is about to work
       on.

   3.  When you're ready you can ask MAKBAS to proceed to create
       the textual database by pushing the "Enter/Return" or "F9"
       function keys.


                       {B}On the Front Panel{N}

You can change the names of the file MAKBAS is going to work with
by moving the cursor to the appropriate field and editing the
text.  You can specify the name of the text that will be stored
in the textual database by modifying "{B}DB Title{N}".  You can give an
initial reference template for this database by entering a
template in the "{B}Starting Ref{N}" area.  Finally, you can tell
MAKBAS to create scratch files on a different device or directory
by coding your device or directory in the "{B}Temporary File Area{N}".



                        {B}MAKBAS SubPanels{N}

You can change other information MAKBAS will use to process your
text by asking TACT to show you the appropriate subpanel, and
then changing its contents.  The subpanels are:

    -  {B}Alphabet{N}: This is the place where you can identify the
       letters of the alphabet and other characters related to
       words.  Type {B}F2{N} for this.

    -  {B}Special Characters{N}: This is the place where you can
       identify bracketting characters that surround text to be
       ignored, brackets that surround COCOA-type references, or
       strings of characters that need to be explicitly coded as
       word-separators.  Type {B}F3{N} for this.

    -  {B}Structural Information{N}: This is the place where you tell
       MAKBAS how to identify and process the structural
       information in your text.  This information can be coded
       as counter characters, or by using BYU or COCOA-type
       references. Type {B}F4{N} for this.


