컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴컴

This is a simplification of the full specification language.  See
the TACT Guide for a more complete description.

All TACT selection criteria specifications start with some type
of initial selection called a {B}source{N}.  Some also contain
{B}refinements{N} or {B}filters{N} that modify the initial selection.
The general form is:

{B}<sources> [ ; <refinements> ]{N}

Note that the refinement section is optional, but, if used, must
be preceded by a semicolon.


                        {B}Selection Sources{N}

The <source> can consist of several selection items separated by
commas:

<source 1> , <source 2> , ...

The following are legal sources:

    o  {B}Vocabulary Words{N}: Any vocabulary word can be given.  If
       the word is reserved within TACT, precede it with an
       (unmatched) '"', e.g. {B}"when{N}.  To manually select words
       from the vocabulary list specify {B}"?{N} as the source.

    o  {B}Regular Expressions{N}: For more information about Regular
       Expression syntax, type "{B}R{N}" now.

    o  {B}Category{N}: To enter a category type "@" followed by the
       category name, e.g.: "{B}@tobe{N}".  You can select a category
       by a list by typing "{B}@?{N}" as a source.

    o  {B}Frequency{N}: The {B}FREQ{N} selection criteria can be used as a
       source or a refinement to select words according to
       frequency of occurrence.  For more information about it
       type "{B}F{N}" now.

    o  {B}Current Selected List{N}: The current selected list can be
       "fed into" the autoselection as a source by including a {B}@{N}
       by itself (not following it by a category name).

    o  {B}SIMIL{N}: The SIMIL selector selects word types based on
       their similarity to a given pattern, e.g.: "{B}SIMIL love{N}
       {B}70%{N}".  This selects words with letter sequences that are
       more than 70% similar to "love".

    o  {B}Phrase Selection{N}: Any of the above selection tools can be
       combined into phrases by joining them with the "{B}|{N}"
       operator, e.g. "{B}my | lov.*{N}" chooses phrases beginning with
       the word "my" and followed immediately by any word
       starting with "lov".  The "{B}>{N}" character can be used to
       select positions other than the first word in the phrase:
       e.g. "{B}my | > lov.*{N}" will save the "lov" words.  The ">"
       character may be placed by itself before or after the
       phrase: "{B}> | my | lov.*{N}" chooses all word immediately
       before the phrase; "{B}my | > | lov.*{N}" chooses all phrases
       beginning with the word "my", followed by any word, and
       then followed by a "lov" word.  The middle, unspecified,
       word is saved in the resulting list.

    o  {B}Co-occurrence Selection{N}: Any of the above selection tools
       can be combined into expressions involving the co-
       occurrence operators "{B}&{N}", "{B}~{N}".  For more information about
       the co-occurrence syntax, type "{B}C{N}" now.

    o  {B}Exclusion{N}: Similarly, the "{B}-{N}" operator can be used:
       <source 1> - <source 2> produces a list of items that are
       in <source 1> but are not in <source 2>.

                      {B}Selection Refinements{N}

A refinement can follow any source or source group.  It begins
with a semicolon.  More than one refinement can be given -- in
which case separate each by a semi-colon:

<sources> ; <refinement> [; <refinement> ...] )

There are several different refinement operators to choose from.
All refinement operators begin with a name, and some are followed
by some further specification information.

    o  {B}FREQ{N}: The FREQ operator can be used as a refinement.  For
       more information about it, type "{B}F{N}" now.

    o  {B}POS{N}: The POS operator needs no further specification
       information.  It transforms each word (type) entry it is
       given into a list of positions where that word occurs:
       e.g: "{B}earth; pos{N}"

    o  {B}REGEXP{N}: Regular expressions can be used as a refinement,
       e.g.: "{B}@goldtheme;  REGEXP a.*{N}" chooses all positions in
       category GoldTheme that are assigned to words beginning
       with the letter "a".  For more information on regular
       expression syntax, type "{B}R{N}" now.

    o  {B}WHEN{N}: Can be used to select positions based on structural
       information in the text.  For more information, type "{B}W{N}"
       now.

    o  {B}SIMIL{N}: The SIMIL operator (described above) can also act
       as a refinement, e.g.: "{B}l.*; simil love 75%{N}" will select
       all words beginning with "l" that are more than 75%
       similar to "love".

    o  {B}SPAN{N}: The SPAN operator creates a resulting list that
       consists of all word tokens "near" to the given inputted
       positions ("near" is defined by the AutoSelection Dialog
       Box's "Config Context").  If the configuration context was
       5 words on either side, for example, the selection "{B}love;{N}
       {B}span{N}" would select all words that occur within 5 words of
       "love" in the text.


