The main reason to use TACT is to produce and examine displays
based on selected positions in the text.  The selected positions
are stored in a {B}selected list{N}.  This single list is used to drive
all the displays.  Hence, one uses TACT essentially (1) by
selecting items you want to look at, and then (2) by looking at
the results with the TACT displays.  Since all displays run from
the same selection, you can switch among the various displays
without needing to recreate the list.

For help on creating the selected list, look at Help item "TACT's
Working Lists".  You can jump there now by pushing "{B}L{N}".

TACT has 5 types of displays:

    o  {B}KWIC Display{N}: shows the selected positions in the text in
       context -- one or more lines surrounding.  For more
       information on the KWIC Display, see Help item "TACT's
       KWIC Display" (push "{B}K{N}" now).

    o  {B}Text Display{N}: shows the selected positions in the body of
       the text.  The text is shown as if you were browsing it
       in, say, a word processor.  For more information on the
       TEXT Display, see Help item "TACT's TEXT Display" (push
       "{B}T{N}" now).

    o  {B}Distribution Display{N}: displays distribution graphs showing
       how the selected positions are scattered through the text,
       or among various textual structural divisions.  For more
       information on the Distribution Display, see Help item
       "TACT's Distribution Display" (push "{B}D{N}" now).

    o  {B}Index Display{N}: generates an index of the positions -- each
       index entry is 1 line.    For more information on the
       Index Display, see Help item "TACT's Index Display" (push
       "{B}I{N}" now).

    o  {B}Collocate Display{N}: generates a list of words near to the
       selected positions.  For more information on the Collocate
       Display, see Help item "TACT's Collocate Display" (push
       "{B}C{N}" now).

The basic way to select a display to look at is to choose it from
the "{B}Current{N}" menu on the action bar.  Once you have selected the
display you can modify some aspects of it by pushing {B}F4{N} and
changing the settings you'll then see.

















