By means of TACT's scripting files you can automatically copy a
sequence of keystrokes during a TACT session, saving them in a
file.  Then, at a future time they can be played back.

Use the "{B}R{N}ecord" item from the Action Bar's "{B}F{N}ile" menu to begin
recording your keystrokes.  Enter the name of a file to use as a
Script file in the dialog box when asked.  To finish recording
once you've started it, type {B}Alt-Esc{N}.  While you are recording
your keystrokes TACT will remind you that you are doing so by
showing "{B}REC{N}" near the right end of the action bar.

To play back a script file use the "pl{B}a{N}y" item from the Action
Bar's "{B}F{N}ile" menu.

Three features are provided while you are recording keystrokes.
These features are meant to make script files more suitable for
teaching use.  For more information about these type "{B}T{N}".







