While you are recording keystrokes to a script file you can use
three special features that are provided to make script files
more suitable for teaching purposes.  All these features put
special codes in the Script file that will cause TACT to do
something special while playing back the file.

To indicate you want to use one of these features type {B}Ctrl-F10{N}.
In response TACT will put up a special Script instruction window
and wait for your response.

Appropriate responses are:

    o  {B}Esc{N}: Type "Esc" if you wish to get out of the special
       feature mode without putting one in the script.

    o  {B}P{N}ause: Type "P" to ask TACT stop while playing back the
       script file and wait for the TACT user to type something
       at the keyboard.  In this way the script user can study
       the screen.

    o  {B}D{N}elay: Type "D" to ask TACT to play back the keystrokes
       from the script file at a slower (or faster rate).
       Normally TACT will play the keystrokes as quickly as it
       can.  If you type "D" TACT will ask you to specify a time
       (in milli-seconds: 1/1000 of a second) that it is to wait
       between keystrokes.  This will allow the script user time
       to watch the script act.  Enter "0" to turn off the delay.
       Legal values are from 100 milliseconds (1/10 second) to
       10000 milliseconds (10 seconds) between keystrokes.

    o  {B}W{N}indow: Type "W" to ask TACT to display a special comment
       window into which you can put text to be displayed during
       script playback.  If you type "W" TACT will put up an
       empty message window into which you can type material you
       want TACT to display on playback.  Use the {B}F5{N} and {B}Ctrl-F5{N}
       keys to resize and move the window to where you want it to
       be.  For more information about creating the text in this
       display window type "{B}W{N}" now.


